fundamental to London’s economic, social, political and cultural development.Migrant City sheds light on the various ways in which newcomers have shaped London life, acting as cheap labour, contributing to the success of its financial sector, its curry houses, and its football clubs. London’s economy has long been driven by migrants, from earlier continental financiers and more recent European Union citizens. Without immigration, fueled by globalization, Panayi argues, London would not have become the world city it is today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aEmigration and immigrationxEconomic aspects. 0aImmigrantszEnglandzLondonxHistory. 0aMulticulturalismzEnglandzLondon. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020 Englishz978311070473008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020z9783110704525oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package Frontlist 2020z978311069231040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300252149423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300252149.jpg  a978-3-11-069231-0  YUP eBook-Package Frontlist 2020b2020  a978-3-11-070471-6  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishb2020  a978-3-11-070473-0  EBOOK PACKAGE History 2020 Englishb2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DEGb2020  aZDB-23-DGGb2020